ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>
[Emus may actually be as sensitive or more sensitive to eastern equine
encephalitis than horses. However, the emu industry began declining several
years ago, and there are not as many of these birds in as many areas as
previously.
Horses need to be vaccinated prior to the onset of mosquito season. The
vaccine is given as series of 2 injections approximately 3 weeks apart.
Generally the Eastern equine encephalitis vaccine is found in combination
with Western and Venezuelan equine encephalitis vaccines. These may also be
found in combination with tetanus toxoid. Generally, there is only a yearly
booster thereafter.
Horse owners that are just now vaccinating for the first time should be aware
that the animal is not fully protected by the vaccine for 2-3 weeks after
vaccination. - Mod.TG]
